Fluorescence emission spectra of CDs and NCDs were investigated in deionized water by various excitation wavelengths in the range of 240–500 nm (Fig. 5
                        ). Fluorescence emission of all CDs and NCDs depended on the excitation wavelength and exhibited mainly fluorescence emission in the visible region with the highest fluorescence intensity by the excitation at 360 nm. Fluorescence intensity of NCDs-EDA (λem = 452 nm/λex = 360 nm) increased 5-fold compared to CDs-6 h, but fluorescence intensity of NCDs-PEI and NCDs-OPD showed less than CDs-6 h (Fig. S3). Since the fluorescence intensity of NCDs-EDA-6 h displayed higher than other NCDs, therefore, the fluorescence emission spectra of NCDs-EDA for 6–24 h were also investigated. The maximum fluorescence emission of NCDs-EDA-12 h and NCDs-EDA-24 h was a blue-shift compared to NCDs-EDA-6 h (Fig. S4). Fluorescence quantum yields of CDs and NCDs were determined by comparing the standard curve of quinine hemisulfate monohydrate (Φ = 54 %) (Figs. S5 and S6). The quantum yield of CDs-24 h exhibited greater than other conditions (Table 1
                        ). These results indicated that the quantum yield of CDs was greater when the increasing time synthesis. Quantum yields of NCDs-PEI displayed less than other nitrogen doping (OPD and EDA). The nitrogen doping effect of the NCDs using ethylenediamine exhibited higher quantum yield due to the increasing surface defects and sp2-hybridized carbon formation on the NCDs [43].
